{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525586"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:16:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:16:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14084"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14084","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14084"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.12,0.62,0.06,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6750"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68214"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6750"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14084"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53671"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"649"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"2117"},{"type":"tags","id":"3467"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14631"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14632"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17976"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37260"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68214","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68214"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a four-day history of left iliac fossa pain, nausea, and vomiting. She has a medical history of hypertension, hypercholesterolaemia, and osteoarthritis. Her regular medications include amlodipine, atorvastatin, and paracetamol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 102/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft with focal tenderness in the left iliac fossa, but no guarding or rebound tenderness. A CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Laparoscopic drainage and washout","Intravenous antibiotics alone","Intravenous antibiotics and percutaneous drainage","Oral antibiotics and outpatient follow-up with CT scan","Sigmoid colectomy + colostomy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features suggestive of complicated diverticulitis. The CT scan shows a large diverticular abscess (Image), which is a known complication of acute diverticulitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous antibiotics and percutaneous drainage\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial management for a large diverticular abscess (typically \u0026gt;4 cm). This approach allows for control of the infection while avoiding immediate surgery in an inflamed field, which carries higher risks of complications. Percutaneous drainage is usually performed under CT or ultrasound guidance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopic drainage and washout\u003C/strong\u003E is not the first-line treatment for a diverticular abscess. Surgery in the acute setting carries higher risks of complications and should be reserved for cases where conservative management fails or if there are signs of peritonitis or perforation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESigmoid colectomy + colostomy\u003C/strong\u003E would be an overly aggressive approach for initial management of a diverticular abscess. This type of surgery is typically reserved for cases of perforated diverticulitis with generalised peritonitis, or for recurrent episodes that have failed conservative management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous antibiotics alone\u003C/strong\u003E, without drainage, may be sufficient for small abscesses (\u0026lt;4 cm) but are usually inadequate for larger collections like the one described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral antibiotics and outpatient follow-up with CT scan\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate for complicated diverticulitis with a large abscess. This approach is more suitable for uncomplicated diverticulitis or for follow-up after successful treatment of a complicated case. In this acute presentation with a large abscess, the patient requires inpatient management with intravenous antibiotics and drainage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing successful drainage and antibiotic therapy, patients often undergo interval colonoscopy to exclude underlying malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Large diverticular abscesses (\u003E4 cm) are best managed with percutaneous drainage and intravenous antibiotics.","CT imaging is crucial for diagnosing and guiding management of complicated diverticulitis.","Colovesical fistula is a potential complication of diverticulitis that may require surgical intervention."],"references":["You H, Cooper M, Von Papern M, Innes J. The management of diverticulitis: a review of the guidelines. Medical Journal of Australia. 2019;211(9). Available at: www.mja.com.au/system/files/issues/211_09/mja250276.pdf","Sartelli, M., Weber, D.G., Kluger, Y. et al. 2020 update of the WSES guidelines for the management of acute colonic diverticulitis in the emergency setting. World J Emerg Surg. 2020. Available at: https://wjes.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s13017-020-00313-4","Gaillard, F., Bell, D. 2008. Hinchey classification of acute diverticulitis. Reference article, Radiopaedia.org. 2024. Available at: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/hinchey-classification-of-acute-diverticulitis","Sacks OA, Hall J. Management of Diverticulitis A Review. JAMA Surgery. 2024. Available at: https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamasurgery/article-abstract/2817649"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53671"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14084"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20968"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21296"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20968","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20968"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/hDpTDzKCruCL5Ceg9e1T4HwISyDf8Y.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/hDpTDzKCruCL5Ceg9e1T4HwISyDf8Y.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":461,"height":461}},{"type":"media","id":"21296","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21296"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8l0HuxrczMFm3D34vgZEEHlI0X4rfM.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8l0HuxrczMFm3D34vgZEEHlI0X4rfM.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":461,"height":461}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53671","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53671"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T15:15:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T15:16:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6750"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68214"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"dat